		 	<span id="comment_score_64653062" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64653062); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Murdoch5">Murdoch5</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Murdoch5">( 1563847 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64653062"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64653062">Reviewing CV's has never been enjoyable, but lately, AI tailoring is the name of the game.  I would say 20%+ are just loaded with "magic numbers", that don't make any sense, combined with lists of words that don't make sense.   It's not usual for me to see N different HTML components listed, "input", "select", "button", "radio", which seems to be an attempt to trick an AI.  <br> <br> I say this because I'll read something like: "Improved system input responsiveness by using selects, gaining a 50% improvement.". Wha</div>
	</div>

